{"cursor":"21807","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox language |name = Classical Arabic |states = Historically in the Middle\nEast, now used as a liturgical language of Islam |era = 4th to 9th centuries;\ncontinues as a liturgical language but with a modernized pronunciation\n|familycolor = Afro-Asiatic |fam2 = Semitic |fam3 = Central Semitic |fam4 =\nArabic |dialects = Over 24 modern Arabic dialects |isoexception=historical |map\n= Large Koran.jpg |mapcaption = Verses from the Qur'an in Classical Arabic,\nwritten in the cursive Arabic script. |notice=IPA }}\n\n\n'Classical Arabic' (CA), also known as Quranic Arabic, is the form of the Arabic\nlanguage used in literary texts from Umayyad and Abbasid times (7th to 9th\ncenturies). It is based on the Medieval dialects of Arab tribes. Modern Standard\nArabic (MSA) is the direct descendant used today throughout the Arab World in\nwriting and in formal speaking, for example, prepared speeches, some radio\nbroadcasts, and non-entertainment content. While the lexis and\nstylistics of Modern Standard Arabic are different from Classical Arabic, the\nmorphology and syntax have remained basically unchanged (though MSA uses a\nsubset of the syntactic structures available in CA). The vernacular\ndialects, however, have changed more dramatically. In the Arab world, little distinction is made between CA and MSA, and\nboth are normally called (â€Ž) in Arabic, meaning \"the most eloquent (Arabic\nlanguage)\".\n\nBecause the Qur'an is written in Classical Arabic, the language is considered by\nmost Muslims to be\nsacred. [http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761576546/Arabic_Language.html\n\"Arabic Language,\"] Microsoft Encarta Online Encyclopedia 2009. \"Classical\nArabic, which has many archaic words, is the sacred language of Islam...\".\n[http://www.webcitation.org/5kwR4ogew Archived] 2009-10-31. It is mostly\nthe language in which Muslims recite their prayers, regardless of what language\nthey use in everyday life.\n","linknr":761,"url":"Classical_Arabic","recorded":1363126755,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Classical_Arabic&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Classical_Arabic&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/Middle_East","/wiki/Islam","/wiki/Liturgical_language","/wiki/Modern_Standard_Arabic","/wiki/Language_family","/wiki/Afroasiatic_languages","/wiki/Semitic_languages","/wiki/Central_Semitic_languages","/wiki/Arabic_languages","/wiki/Arabic_dialects","/wiki/ISO_639-3","/wiki/File:Large_Koran.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Large_Koran.jpg/300px-Large_Koran.jpg","/wiki/Qur%27an","/wiki/Cursive","/wiki/Arabic_alphabet","/wiki/International_Phonetic_Alphabet","/wiki/Unicode","/wiki/Help:IPA","/wiki/Mojibake","/wiki/Unicode","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Arabic_albayancalligraphy.svg/40px-Arabic_albayancalligraphy.svg.png","/wiki/Arabic_script","/wiki/Help:Arabic","/wiki/Arabic_script","/wiki/Quran","/wiki/Arabic_language","/wiki/Umayyad_Caliphate","/wiki/Abbasid_Caliphate","/wiki/Tribes_of_Arabia","/wiki/Modern_Standard_Arabic","/wiki/Arab_World","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Lexis_(linguistics)","/wiki/Stylistics_(linguistics)","/wiki/Morpho